			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Crowd Control<a name="69462"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Nov 10 04 4:42 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I never really understood how chanters feel when some broke a mez on an add until I started using my bards mez songs so much in BoT...</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
If you really want to understand the chanter perspective, you should take it two steps further:
<br />

<br />
(1) take off all your plate armor and wear only silk.
<br />
(2) root the mob and sit right next to it so that it will be sure to pound the holy bajeezus out of you each and every time someone breaks the mez
<br />

<br />
This will give you a closer approximation to what enchanters are looking at, and possibly a sense of why they tend to yell at people for breaking mezzes.
<br />

<br />
p.s. arrows can strike targets other than what you have targeted if you're not careful about line of sight. The ranger may not have known this (he should have) and may have thought that by targetting the correct mob that he could safely shoot arrows past/through the mezzed mob. This can be especially annoying in LDoNs where arrows have a tendency to hit the pet/trap mobs lying all over the place.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
